'''Peter Martin Anker''' (June 20, 1801 – February 24, 1863) was a Norwegian landholder and politician. [[File:Rød Herregård.JPG|thumb|Rød Herregård in Halden]] Anker was born at [[Halden]] in [[Østfold]], Norway. He was a son of wholesaler Niels Anker (1764–1812). He was also a third cousin of Karen Anker, wife of [[Johan Caspar Herman Wedel-Jarlsberg]].<ref name=snl2>{{cite encyclopedia|year=2007|title=Anker|encyclopedia=[[Store norske leksikon]]|editor=Henriksen, Petter|publisher=Kunnskapsforlaget|location=Oslo|url=http://www.snl.no/Anker|first=Terje|last=Bratberg|language=Norwegian|accessdate=11 June 2010}}</ref> Together with Thrine Gløersen (1814–1902)<ref name=nbl>{{cite encyclopedia|year=|title=Dikka Møller|encyclopedia=[[Norsk biografisk leksikon]]|first=Elisabeth|last=Lønnå|editor=[[Knut Helle|Helle, Knut]]|publisher=Kunnskapsforlaget|location=Oslo|url=http://www.snl.no/.nbl_biografi/Dikka_Møller/utdypning|language=Norwegian|accessdate=11 June 2010}}</ref> he had the children [[Nils Anker]], [[Herman Anker]], [[Christian August Anker]] and Dikka Møller. Grandchildren include [[Katti Anker Møller]], [[Ella Anker]] and [[Johan Anker]] and great-greandchildren include [[Øyvind Anker]], [[Synnøve Anker Aurdal]], [[Peter Martin Anker (diplomat)|Peter Martin Anker]]<ref name=snl2/> and [[Tove Mohr]].<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|year=|title=Ella Anker|encyclopedia=[[Norsk biografisk leksikon]]|first=Svennik|last=Høyer|authorlink=Svennik Høyer|editor=[[Knut Helle|Helle, Knut]]|publisher=Kunnskapsforlaget|location=Oslo|url=http://www.snl.no/.nbl_biografi/Ella_Anker/utdypning|language=Norwegian|accessdate=13 June 2010}}</ref>
He served as first deputy to the [[Parliament of Norway]] during the term 1839–1841, representing the constituency [[Østfold|Smaalenenes Amt]] (now Østfold). <ref name=snl2/><ref name=nsd>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nsd.uib.no/polsys/index.cfm?urlname=polsys&lan=&MenuItem=N1_1&ChildItem=&State=collapse&UttakNr=33&person=10138|title=Peder Martin Anker|publisher=Norwegian Social Science Data Services (NSD)|language=Norwegian|accessdate=11 June 2010}}</ref>
Anker was a major landowner and held the manor house Rød herregård in Halden. <ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.visitnorway.com/listings/herreg%C3%A5rdskaf%C3%A9en-r%C3%B8d-herreg%C3%A5rd/333/|title= Herregårdskaféen - Rød Herregård|publisher=visitnorway.com|accessdate= June 15, 2016}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web|url= http://ostfoldmuseene.no/avdelingene/halden-historiske-samlinger/rod-herregaard-og-rods-hage/|title= Om Rød Herregård|publisher= Østfoldmuseene|accessdate= June 15, 2016|deadurl= yes|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160812052513/http://ostfoldmuseene.no/avdelingene/halden-historiske-samlinger/rod-herregaard-og-rods-hage/|archivedate= 12 August 2016|df= dmy-all}}</ref> Anker was married to Petronelle Didrikke Cathrine Tank (1806-1833) daughter of [[Carsten Tank]]. Following her death, he married Cathrine Olava Nicoline Gløersen (1814-1902).<ref>{{cite web|url= https://snl.no/Carsten_Tank|title= Carsten Tank|publisher= Store norske leksikon|author= Knut Dørum |accessdate= June 15, 2016}}</ref>
